Alembic is used to migrate the databases. [link](https://alembic.sqlalchemy.org/en/latest/front.html#installation)

# How to

Requirements:
1. Set credentials for Azure authentication towards the postgres database. The
   set of credential types to try is controlled by `ISAR_ALLOWED_AUTH_METHODS`,
   a comma-separated list whose entries may be `WorkloadIdentity` (uses the
   federated token file mounted in the pod by Azure Workload Identity in AKS)
   and/or `ClientSecret` (reads `ISAR_AZURE_CLIENT_SECRET`). When more than one
   method is configured, the order determines the priority inside the resulting
   `ChainedTokenCredential`. The default is `ClientSecret`, which is what
   `alembic env.py` uses when running locally.

<details>
<summary>
Creating new migrations
</summary>

```bash
alembic revision --autogenerate -m "Migration name"
```

This will compare what is in the metadata of sqlalchemy Base with what is in the database and create a migration for it. 
</details>

<details open>
<summary>
Checking if database is up-to-date
</summary>

```bash
alembic check
```
</details>

<details>
<summary>
Run migrations
</summary>

```bash
alembic upgrade head
```
</details>


# Notes:
1. The model files are located [here](../src/isar/services/service_connections/persistent_memory.py). 
